%S A397083 2,23,223,1223,31223,231223,6231223,61231223,661231223,5661231223,
%T A397083 56161231223,526161231223,5216161231223,25216161231223,
%U A397083 425216161231223,6425216161231223,66425216161231223,664325216161231223,9664325216161231223,29664325216161231223,296764325216161231223,2996764325216161231223
%N A397083 Start with a(1) = 2; to get a(n+1) insert in a(n) at the leftmost possible position the smallest possible digit such that the new number is a prime.
%C A397083 This is the left-right counterpart of A356557. It uses the same precedence of the insertion position over smallness of the inserted digit, but considers positions from left to right instead of from right to left.
%C A397083 Together with A356557, A357436, and A397084, this sequence belongs to the family obtained by choosing the precedence between digit smallness and insertion position, and the direction in which insertion positions are considered.
%C A397083 Leftmostness of the insertion position has precedence over smallness of the inserted digit.
%C A397083 Prepending a digit 0 is not allowed.
%C A397083 If no prime extension exists, the sequence terminates.
%C A397083 The number a(n) has n decimal digits.
%C A397083 The sequence terminates if and only if it contains a term of A125001.
%C A397083 Is the sequence infinite?
%H A397083 Michael S. Branicky, <a href="/A397083/b397083.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..1000</a>
%e A397083 a(3) = 223. Starting from 23, the leftmost position is checked first. Prepending 1 gives 123, which is composite, while prepending 2 gives the prime 223.
%e A397083 a(8) = 61231223. Starting from 6231223, no prepended digit produces a prime. At the second insertion position, inserting 1 gives the prime 61231223.
%t A397083 a[1]=2; a[n_]:=a[n]=Catch@Module[{digits=IntegerDigits[a[n - 1]],candidate},
%t A397083 Do[If[position == 1 && digit == 0, Continue[]];candidate = FromDigits@Insert[digits, digit, position];If[PrimeQ[candidate], Throw[candidate]],{position, 1, Length[digits] + 1},{digit, 0, 9}]]; Array[a, 22]
%o A397083 (Python)
%o A397083 from sympy import isprime
%o A397083 from itertools import islice
%o A397083 def anext(an):
%o A397083     s = str(an)
%o A397083     for k in range(len(s)+1):
%o A397083         for c in "0123456789"[int(k==0):]:
%o A397083             w = s[:k] + c + s[k:]
%o A397083             if isprime(int(w)): return int(w)
%o A397083 def agen(an=2):
%o A397083     while an != None: yield an; an = anext(an)
%o A397083 print(list(islice(agen(), 22))) # _Michael S. Branicky_, Jun 16 2026
%Y A397083 Cf. A356557, the right-to-left counterpart, in which the insertion position also has precedence over smallness of the inserted digit.
%Y A397083 Cf. A397084, which also considers insertion positions from left to right, but gives precedence to smallness of the inserted digit over leftmostness of position.
%Y A397083 Cf. A357436, in which smallness of the inserted digit has precedence and insertion positions are considered from right to left.
%Y A397083 Cf. A125001, A332603.
%K A397083 nonn,base
